{
  "id": "lord-holmes-ai-bill",
  "name": "Lord Holmes AI Bill",
  "desc": "Statutory horizontal AI governance that codifies citizen protection, creative IP consent, and public engagement through a new AI Authority — closing the gap the UK's voluntary approach leaves open.",
  "caveat": "This stance is a good-faith categorisation based on public information including parliamentary records, published reports, and speeches. It has not been reviewed or endorsed by Lord Holmes or his office and this analysis of his positions should not be attributed to him.",
  "picks": {
    "Capability Class": {
      "value": "Frontier",
      "memo": "Holmes's bill targets frontier-scale systems where citizen exposure is highest and voluntary governance is most inadequate.",
      "detail": "The bill addresses AI systems broadly but its urgency stems from frontier capability. The '8 Realities' report documents harms from large-scale generative systems: deepfake disinformation, voice-cloning fraud, algorithmic welfare decisions, and copyright-scale training ingestion. The bill's definition explicitly includes generative AI. Narrow or tool-grade systems would not generate the regulatory gap the bill seeks to close."
    },
    "Domain Breadth": {
      "value": "General",
      "memo": "The bill's horizontal regulatory design and cross-domain citizen archetypes address general-purpose AI, not sector-bounded systems.",
      "detail": "Holmes's eight citizen archetypes span voting, fraud, welfare, employment, education, healthcare, and creative industries. His deliberate choice of horizontal regulation over sector-specific rules reflects the general-purpose nature of the systems he targets. A sector-specific approach would leave gaps between regulators. The horizontal AI Authority exists precisely because AI capability crosses domain boundaries."
    },
    "Capability Trajectory": {
      "value": "Rapid",
      "memo": "Holmes frames regulatory urgency around rapid capability growth that is outpacing governance institutions.",
      "detail": "Between the bill's first introduction (November 2023) and reintroduction (March 2025), Holmes's language escalated from 'urgent' to 'even more urgent.' This framing implies capability is advancing faster than institutions can respond through voluntary measures. The rapid trajectory justifies statutory intervention: if progress were incremental, existing regulators could adapt. The bill's adaptive design anticipates continued rapid change."
    },
    "Research Automation": {
      "value": "Human-led",
      "memo": "Holmes's governance framework assumes human-directed AI development with institutional oversight at every level.",
      "detail": "The bill's AI Responsible Officer, transparency requirements, and human-oversight principles all assume humans lead AI development and deployment. Research automation is not addressed because the bill's concern is governance of deployed capability, not the research process. The human-led assumption is consistent with Holmes's insistence that regulation enables innovation through human direction."
    },
    "Unhobbling": {
      "value": "Tool-using",
      "memo": "Holmes legislates for AI systems that take delegated actions within enterprise workflows — tool-using but governed.",
      "detail": "The AI Responsible Officer clause presumes AI is integrated into business processes making consequential decisions: screening job applicants, processing benefit claims, generating content. These are tool-using deployments, not chatbot conversations. The bill's consent and labelling requirements only make sense if AI systems produce consequential outputs. The regulatory sandbox clause assumes tool-using deployment in real markets."
    },
    "Replication Scale": {
      "value": "Population-scale",
      "memo": "The '8 Billion Reasons' framing and cross-society citizen archetypes position the bill against population-scale AI exposure.",
      "detail": "Holmes's report title is not rhetorical. The eight citizen archetypes — voter, scammed, benefit claimant, job seeker, teenager, creative, transplant patient, teacher — represent categories that collectively cover the entire population. His argument is that unregulated AI affects everyone, often without their knowledge. The public-engagement clause confirms the population-scale framing: the AI Authority must reach the whole public."
    },
    "Operating Speed": {
      "value": "Faster-than-human",
      "memo": "Holmes's emphasis on AI outpacing human institutions implies faster-than-human operational speed as the governance challenge.",
      "detail": "The bill's urgency derives from AI acting faster than regulatory institutions can respond. Voice-cloning scams, algorithmic welfare decisions, and training-data ingestion all operate at machine speed. Holmes's solution — statutory principles rather than case-by-case review — is designed for a faster-than-human operational environment where voluntary governance cannot keep pace."
    },
    "Physical World Extension": {
      "value": "Cognitive-only",
